Terraform AWS Infrastructure Setup

This repository contains Terraform code to provision a complete AWS infrastructure including:

VPC with public subnets

EC2 instances running Apache web servers

Application Load Balancer (ALB)

Target Group with health checks

Security Groups

User-data scripts for EC2 bootstrapping

Key Pair integration for SSH access

📁 Project Structure

├── main.tf              # Entry point for Terraform configuration
├── vpc.tf               # VPC, subnets, route tables, IGW
├── ec2.tf               # EC2 instances and key pair reference
├── alb.tf               # Load Balancer and Target Group
├── userdata.mk          # User-data script for Webserver1
├── userdata1.mk         # User-data script for Webserver2
├── variables.tf         # Input variables
├── outputs.tf           # Output values
├── terraform.tfstate    # Terraform state file (not committed)

🚀 Deployment Steps

1. Initialize Terraform

terraform init

2. Review the plan

terraform plan

3. Apply the configuration

terraform apply

4. Destroy the infrastructure (if needed)

terraform destroy

🔐 Key Pair Setup

Ensure your AWS key pair exists and is referenced correctly in ec2.tf:

key_name = "key pair"

Do not commit your .pem file to GitHub. Add it to .gitignore:

*.pem
terraform.tfstate
terraform.tfstate.backup
.terraform/

🌐 Architecture Overview

Users access the application via the ALB

ALB forwards traffic to EC2 instances in two public subnets

EC2 instances run Apache and serve content from user-data scripts

Security Groups allow HTTP and SSH access

Key pair enables SSH login for troubleshooting

📸 Diagram

Refer to the architecture diagram in the /assets folder for a visual overview.

🧰 Tools Used

Terraform

AWS EC2, VPC, ALB

Apache

📌 Notes

Ensure your AWS credentials are configured via CLI or environment variables

Use terraform apply -replace="aws_instance.Webserver1" to recreate EC2 with updated key

